  <!-- Lesson 1: The Playbook Voice                                       -->
  <!-- ================================================================== -->
  <section id="playbook-voice" data-slide-index="0" data-lesson-slug="playbook-voice" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>The Playbook Voice</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      Most player education content has no personality. Playbook sounds like somebody. This lesson tells you who.
    </p>

    <p>
      It reads like it was written by a committee of lawyers told to "make it sound helpful." The result: content that sounds like nobody — generic, cautious, and forgettable.
    </p>

    <h3 id="at-the-table-not-in-the-booth">At the table, not in the booth</h3>

    <p>
      The Playbook voice isn't above you. It's at the table with you. It knows the odds. It's read
      the fine print. It understands the mechanics behind every game. But it doesn't lecture. It
      doesn't wag a finger. It doesn't treat you like a student or a patient. It treats you like a
      smart adult who deserves the full picture.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="The Personality Test" icon="target">
      <p>
        Imagine someone at a poker table who knows the odds, calls out the myths, keeps the game
        fun, and quietly has the number for support if you ever need it — but doesn't bring it up
        unless you hint at needing it. Does your content sound like it was written by that person? If yes, ship it.
      </p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <h3 id="five-voice-traits">Five voice traits</h3>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-3 my-6">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-teal/20 bg-teal/5 p-4">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-teal/15 flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-teal-dark" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M12 6.253v13m0-13C10.832 5.477 9.246 5 7.5 5S4.168 5.477 3 6.253v13C4.168 18.477 5.754 18 7.5 18s3.332.477 4.5 1.253m0-13C13.168 5.477 14.754 5 16.5 5c1.747 0 3.332.477 4.5 1.253v13C19.832 18.477 18.247 18 16.5 18c-1.746 0-3.332.477-4.5 1.253"/></svg>
          </span>
          <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm">Knowledgeable</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 leading-relaxed">Knows the math — house edge, RNG, probability — but explains it like something interesting at a bar, not a research paper.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-teal/20 bg-teal/5 p-4">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-teal/15 flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-teal-dark" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m5.618-4.016A11.955 11.955 0 0112 2.944a11.955 11.955 0 01-8.618 3.04A12.02 12.02 0 003 9c0 5.591 3.824 10.29 9 11.622 5.176-1.332 9-6.03 9-11.622 0-1.042-.133-2.052-.382-3.016z"/></svg>
          </span>
          <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm">Confident</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 leading-relaxed">Doesn't hedge or equivocate. Knows what it's talking about — but never makes you feel stupid for not knowing already.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-teal/20 bg-teal/5 p-4">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-teal/15 flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-teal-dark" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M12 8v13m0-13V6a2 2 0 112 2h-2zm0 0V5.5A2.5 2.5 0 109.5 8H12zm-7 4h14M5 12a2 2 0 110-4h14a2 2 0 110 4M5 12v7a2 2 0 002 2h10a2 2 0 002-2v-7"/></svg>
          </span>
          <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm">Generous</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 leading-relaxed">Shares because you should have it. Not because it's required to. Because information is better when shared.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-teal/20 bg-teal/5 p-4">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-teal/15 flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-teal-dark" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M17 20h5v-2a3 3 0 00-5.356-1.857M17 20H7m10 0v-2c0-.656-.126-1.283-.356-1.857M7 20H2v-2a3 3 0 015.356-1.857M7 20v-2c0-.656.126-1.283.356-1.857m0 0a5.002 5.002 0 019.288 0M15 7a3 3 0 11-6 0 3 3 0 016 0z"/></svg>
          </span>
          <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm">At the table</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 leading-relaxed">The perspective comes from inside the experience, not outside looking in. Understands gambling as entertainment, not a lab subject.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-teal/20 bg-teal/5 p-4">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-teal/15 flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-teal-dark" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M4.318 6.318a4.5 4.5 0 000 6.364L12 20.364l7.682-7.682a4.5 4.5 0 00-6.364-6.364L12 7.636l-1.318-1.318a4.5 4.5 0 00-6.364 0z"/></svg>
          </span>
          <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm">Non-judgmental</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 leading-relaxed">Will tell you your "system" doesn't work — but never in a way that makes you feel stupid for trying it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 id="what-the-voice-is-not">What the voice is NOT</h3>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-3 my-6">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-danger/15 bg-danger/5 p-3 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-danger/10 items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-2">
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-danger" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M18 6L6 18M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">Not a teacher</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-snug">Conversation, not class.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-danger/15 bg-danger/5 p-3 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-danger/10 items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-2">
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-danger" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M18 6L6 18M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">Not a doctor</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-snug">Shares info. You decide.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-danger/15 bg-danger/5 p-3 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-danger/10 items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-2">
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-danger" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M18 6L6 18M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">Not a parent</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-snug">Trusts you to be an adult.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-danger/15 bg-danger/5 p-3 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-danger/10 items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-2">
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-danger" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M18 6L6 18M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
        </span>
        <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">Not a killjoy</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-snug">Gambling is fun. Eyes open.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Sub-section: Five voice dimensions -->
  <section id="the-five-voice-dimensions" data-slide-index="0" data-lesson-slug="playbook-voice" class="module-section py-16">
    <h3 id="five-voice-dimensions-heading">The five voice dimensions</h3>

    <p>
      The brand book defines five dimensions that shape how Playbook sounds. Each one is a spectrum
      with a default setting and guardrails. Internalize all five and you can write on-brand content
      for any context.
    </p>

    <h3 id="1-voice">1. Voice — how the brand sounds</h3>

    <p>
      Playbook sounds like a peer — someone at the table with you. Confident, conversational,
      no credentials cited. Not an authority lecturing from a podium, not a clinician reading from
      a chart. Trust is built through relatability, not titles.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The line:</strong> "Here's how it works" is peer voice. "Many players don't realize..."
      is authority voice pretending to be helpful. The first shares information. The second implies
      the reader is behind.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Authority vs Peer Voice">
      <p>
        <strong>Authority / Clinical:</strong> "Contrary to what many players believe, slot machine outcomes are determined by random number generators, not by previous results."
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Peer:</strong> "Here's how slot machines actually decide what to show you. It's called RNG, and it's more interesting than you'd think."
      </p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <h3 id="2-framing">2. Framing — how information is presented</h3>

    <p>
      Playbook frames information as a personal opportunity, not a collective warning. "Your bankroll,"
      "your odds," "your decision." The reader is an autonomous agent making choices — not a patient
      receiving a diagnosis.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The line:</strong> Frame benefits as things the reader gains, not harms the reader avoids.
      "Know the odds so you can play smarter" is opportunity. "Be aware that gambling can lead to
      financial harm" is warning.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Warning vs Opportunity Framing">
      <p>
        <strong>Warning framing:</strong> "Be aware that continued gambling may result in financial losses that exceed your budget."
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Opportunity framing:</strong> "Set a budget before you play. Decide what you're comfortable spending — and stop when you reach it. Your bankroll, your call."
      </p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <h3 id="3-humor">3. Humor — how and when wit is used</h3>

    <p>
      Playbook uses humor to earn attention and make information memorable. It does <em>not</em> use
      moral authority to lecture players about what they should do. In Tier 1 content (education,
      social, quizzes), the default register is irreverent. In Tier 2 content (support, crisis,
      take-a-break), humor drops to zero.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The line:</strong> Humor directed at myths, misconceptions, and the absurdity of
      superstitions. Never humor directed at players who are struggling.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Preachy vs Witty">
      <p>
        <strong>Preachy:</strong> "Players should be aware that no gambling system can overcome the mathematical house advantage in the long run."
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Witty:</strong> "Think you've got a 'system' that beats the house? Cool. The house has a system too. It's called math. Let's compare notes."
      </p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <h3 id="4-directness">4. Directness — how blunt or soft the delivery is</h3>

    <p>
      Playbook's default is blunt. It states conclusions plainly and backs them with evidence.
      No softening, no hedging. "This bet is terrible. Here's why." The reader gets the facts
      first and decides what to do with them.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The line:</strong> Blunt is honest and clear. Harsh is judgmental. "This is one of the
      worst bets on the floor" is blunt. "Only a fool would take this bet" is harsh.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Hedging vs Blunt">
      <p>
        <strong>Hedging:</strong> "Some players may find it useful to consider that certain wagers carry a higher expected cost, and it may be worth researching the differences."
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Blunt:</strong> "The house edge on American roulette is 5.26%. That's one of the worst bets on the casino floor. Now you know."
      </p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <h3 id="5-comfort">5. Comfort — how the brand handles sensitive topics</h3>

    <p>
      Playbook treats gambling as entertainment — discussed the way you'd discuss movies, sports,
      or dining out. The words "gambling," "betting," and "playing" appear freely. Content assumes
      the reader is an active player, and that's fine. It normalizes without dramatizing.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The line:</strong> Open and comfortable is not the same as flippant. Gambling is fun,
      and the content reflects that — but it never dismisses the reality that some players need
      support. It holds both truths without making either one weird.
    </p>

    <KeyConcept title="Stigmatizing vs Comfortable">
      <p>
        <strong>Stigmatizing:</strong> "WARNING: Gambling can be addictive. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, call the helpline immediately."
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Comfortable:</strong> "Every time you play, you're making decisions. Some are better than others. This guide helps you see which is which. And if you ever want to talk, free support is available 24/7."
      </p>
    </KeyConcept>

    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>
        The Playbook voice is one person: knowledgeable, confident, generous, at the table with you.
        It corrects without judgment and treats gambling as entertainment. Five dimensions define how
        it sounds: Voice (peer, not authority), Framing (opportunity, not warning), Humor (witty, not
        preachy), Directness (blunt, not hedging), and Comfort (open, not stigmatizing). Get all five
        right and the content writes itself.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

  <!-- ================================================================== -->
  <!-- Lesson 2: Stigma-Free Language                                     -->
  <!-- ================================================================== -->
  <section id="stigma-free-language" data-slide-index="1" data-lesson-slug="stigma-free-language" class="module-section py-16">
    <h2>Stigma-Free Language</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-n600 mb-6">
      Language shapes perception. The words on the screen decide whether someone stays or clicks away. When players encounter clinical language — "problem gambler," "warning signs," "gambling addiction" — they assume the content isn't for them. So they leave. This isn't about political correctness. It's about effectiveness.
    </p>

    <h3 id="the-10-essential-swaps">The 10 essential swaps</h3>

    <p>These apply to all Tier 1 content — social posts, app copy, email, print, in-venue signage:</p>

    <StigmaSwapGame client:visible />

    <h3 id="phrases-to-retire">Phrases to retire</h3>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-3 my-6">
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-danger/30 bg-danger/5 p-4 shadow-sm">
        <span class="inline-block text-xs font-heading font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-danger bg-danger/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded mb-2">Retire</span>
        <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy mb-1.5">"Gamble Responsibly"</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 mb-2">Nobody has ever changed behavior because of this phrase. Zero actionable content.</p>
        <div class="pt-2 border-t border-danger/15">
          <p class="text-xs font-heading font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-teal-dark mb-0.5">Replace with</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-navy font-semibold">"Know the odds." / "Set your budget." / "Check your session."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-orange/30 bg-orange/5 p-4 shadow-sm">
        <span class="inline-block text-xs font-heading font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-orange bg-orange/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded mb-2">Retire</span>
        <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy mb-1.5">"When the fun stops, stop."</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 mb-2">Assumes players can self-diagnose in the moment. Many players experiencing difficulty still report "fun."</p>
        <div class="pt-2 border-t border-orange/15">
          <p class="text-xs font-heading font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-teal-dark mb-0.5">Replace with</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-navy font-semibold">"Set your limits before you play."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-warning/30 bg-warning/5 p-4 shadow-sm">
        <span class="inline-block text-xs font-heading font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-warning bg-warning/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded mb-2">Retire</span>
        <p class="font-heading font-semibold text-navy mb-1.5">"If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, call X."</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-n700 mb-2">Only reaches people who already identify a problem. Excludes everyone else.</p>
        <div class="pt-2 border-t border-warning/15">
          <p class="text-xs font-heading font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-teal-dark mb-0.5">Replace with</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-navy font-semibold">"Free, confidential support — for any question about gambling."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

