          <span class="flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-navy text-white text-sm font-heading font-bold shrink-0">1</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">How direct can we be?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-relaxed">Can we say "This bet is terrible" or should we show the comparison and let the reader draw conclusions?</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-n100 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-navy text-white text-sm font-heading font-bold shrink-0">2</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">What's the humor ceiling?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-relaxed">Can we be cheeky? Dry? Or should humor be almost invisible?</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-n100 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-navy text-white text-sm font-heading font-bold shrink-0">3</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">How is gambling culturally framed?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-relaxed">As entertainment? As a social activity? As something private? The cultural frame affects which voice traits to emphasize.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-n100 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-navy text-white text-sm font-heading font-bold shrink-0">4</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-heading font-bold text-navy text-sm mb-1">What pronouns and perspective feel natural?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-n600 leading-relaxed">"You" is universal, but some markets prefer "we" (communal) or third-person framing for sensitive topics.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="text-sm text-n500 mt-4">
      The brand book's Cultural Adaptation Guide (Chapter 9) provides the full five-spectrum
      framework — Voice, Framing, Humor, Directness, and Comfort — with pre-written variant
      libraries covering 217+ messages across all dimensions.
    </p>

    <KeyTakeaway>
      <p>
        The voice is universal. The expression adapts. Humor can be bold, understated, or minimal —
        all are valid as long as the content doesn't read like a compliance form. Directness can be
        blunt, diplomatic, or contextual — all are honest. Adapt the dialect, never the character.
      </p>
    </KeyTakeaway>
  </section>

